# function to create a circle
circle <- function(center = c(0, 0), npoints = 100) {
    r = 1
    tt = seq(0, 2 * pi, length = npoints)
    xx = center[1] + r * cos(tt)
    yy = center[1] + r * sin(tt)
    return(data.frame(x = xx, y = yy))
}
corcir = circle(c(0, 0), npoints = 100)

# data frame with arrows coordinates
loads <- unclass(burrito.FA.none$loadings)
arrows = data.frame(x1 = rep(0, ncol(burrito.loged.scaled)), y1 = rep(0, ncol(burrito.loged.scaled)), x2 = loads[,1], 
    y2 = loads[,2])

# geom_path will do open circles
ggplot() + geom_path(data = corcir, aes(x = x, y = y), colour = "gray65") + 
    geom_segment(data = arrows, aes(x = x1, y = y1, xend = x2, yend = y2), colour = "gray65") + 
    geom_text(data =as.data.frame(loads), aes(x = MR2, y = MR1, label = rownames(loads))) + 
    geom_hline(yintercept = 0, colour = "gray65") + geom_vline(xintercept = 0, 
    colour = "gray65") + xlim(-1.1, 1.1) + ylim(-1.1, 1.1) + labs(x = "F1", 
    y = "F2") + ggtitle("Circle of correlations")

factor scores

Factor Scores, :

  • Validity factor score factor score ;
  • Univocality factor score ( );
  • Correlation Preserving factor scores (\(cor(\hat{\mathbb{V}}) = \mathbb{I}\));
\begin{align*} \mathbb{R} = \mathbb{S}^\mathrm{T}\mathbb{W}\mathbb{L}^{-1}, \end{align*}

factor scores .

  • \(\mathbb{S} = \mathbb{F}(\mathbf{W}^\mathrm{T}\mathbf{W})^{-1}\) Factor Structure, \(\mathbf{W}\) . \(\mathbb{S} = \mathbb{F}\);
  • \(\mathbb{C} = \mathbb{W}^\mathrm{T}cor(\mathbb{Y})\mathbb{W}\) factor scores, \(\mathbb{W}\) , factor scores;
  • \(\mathbb{L} = sqrt(diag(\mathbb{C}))\) , sd .

validity, univocality.

, \(\mathbb{R}\):

scores.factor.correlation <- function(fa.object, data.cor.matrix){
  C <- t(fa.object$weights) %*% data.cor.matrix %*% fa.object$weights
  L <- (diag(C))
  L <- sqrt(L)
  L <- diag(L)
  R <- t(fa.object$Structure) %*% fa.object$weights %*% solve(L)
  return(R)
}

\(\hat{\mathbb{V}} = \mathbb{WY}\). \begin{align*} \mathbb{W} = cor(\mathbb{Y})^{-1} \mathbb{F} \end{align*}

r.scores factor scores. fa factor scores, regression method (Thurstone). r.scores, ! :

  • scores The factor scores as requested. Note that these scores reflect the choice of the way scores should be estimated (see scores in the input). That is, simple regression (Thurstone), correlaton preserving (tenBerge) as well as Anderson and Bartlett using the appropriate algorithms (see factor.scores). The correlation between factor score estimates (r.scores) is based upon using the regression/Thurstone approach. The actual correlation between scores will reflect the rotation algorithm chosen and may be found by correlating those scores.

Berge scores

Anderson .

\begin{align*} \mathbb{L} = \mathbb{F}\mathbb{\Phi}^{1/2}, \quad \mathbb{C} = cor(\mathbb{Y})^{-1/2} \mathbb{L} (\mathbb{L}^\mathrm{T} cor(\mathbb{Y})^{-1} \mathbb{L})^{-1/2}, \quad \mathbb{W} = (\mathbb{F}^\mathrm{T}\mathbb{F})^{-1/2} \mathbb{C} \mathbb{\Phi}^{1/2}, \end{align*}

\(\mathbb{\Phi}\) common factors correlation matrix (\(\mathbb{E}\mathbb{\eta\eta}^\mathrm{T}\))
